<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910211-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>910211-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Fairchild Corp.:   Unit Gets Court Approval   For Settlement of Charges</HL><DATE>02/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   FA</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   Fairchild Corp. said an aerospace-parts testing unitreceived federal court approval of its settlement of federalcriminal charges of improperly testing fasteners.   Fairchild, based in Chantilly, Va., said VSI Inc. will paythe government $2.5 million in punitive damages and about $1million for court costs. The settlement was approved in U.S.District Court in Seattle.</LP><TEXT>   Last May, VSI pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy tosubmit false claims, and agreed to pay the damages. VSI,which has already paid $14.5 million in civil penalties, saidthe court approval concludes actions taken against it by theDepartment of Justice under the federal False Claims Act.   Last year, federal prosecutors charged the unit withgenerating fraudulent testing documents at its Chatsworth,Calif. plant, which tested special nuts, bolts and otherfasteners used on most U.S. commercial jetliners and militaryaircraft. Fairchild has maintained that air safety was&quot;never&quot; compromised as a result of testing discrepancies atthat plant.</TEXT></DOC>